query.result:
13 “Oh, dear little bird of mine who so pushes yourself, 14 that, as earthly minds see 15 not to fit in a triangle two obtuse angles,
16 so you see contingent things 17 before they are in themselves, looking at the point 18 to which all times are present;
19 while I was joined to Virgil 20 up the mountain that cares for the souls 21 and descending into the dead world,
22 were given to me outside of my future life 23 words heavy, although I feel myself 24 quite tetragonal to the blows of fortune;
25 for which my will would be content 26 to understand what fortune approaches me: 27 because a foreseen arrow comes more slowly.”

